<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-475-399  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 475 399.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 6 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK: British Telecom plans to tackle market liberalization.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gold, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (telecommunication policy).andO;Topic:     Telephone companiesTelecommunicationsUnited KingdomLegal IssuesDeregulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK: BRITISH TELECOM PLANS TO TACKLE MARKET LIBERALIZATION LONDON, ENGLAND,1990 AUG 6 (NB) -- British Telecom (BT) Chairman Iain Vallance has revealedsome of his plans for tackling the thorny problem of the liberalization ofthe UK telecommunications market.andM;Speaking at BT's annual general meeting in Nottingham, Vallance said that,while both BT and the government agree on the concept of the necessity of afree market if value for money services are to develop, there are a number ofkey issues that BT must solve.andM;&quot;To achieve this there are a number of issues that will have to be addressed.andO;One of the most important is to tackle the fundamental imbalance in BritishTelecom's pricing structure.andP;  Customers who make a lot of telephone callssubsidize those who make less frequent use of the phone,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;For historical reasons, what we charge for renting a line falls well shortof the cost of providing and maintaining that line.andP;  And this shortfall hasto be recovered from the relatively high margin we make on calls,particularly long-distance and international calls,&quot; he added.andM;Vallance went on to say that, because BT's prices for calls are higher thanthey might otherwise be, competitors can undercut BT pricing, particularly inproviding services to companies and individuals who make a lot of calls.andM;&quot;Since we have to provide a vast number of unprofitable lines to smallerusers, we are unable to respond in pricing terms,&quot; he said, adding thatresidential customers will not notice the effects of the increasedcompetition.andM;&quot;At the other end of the scale - the residential area which receives thebenefit of the cross-subsidy - there is little or no incentive forcompetitors to enter the market.&quot;andM;(Steve Gold/19900806/British Telecom - Tel: 071-356-5369)</TEXT></DOC>